      <h1>US State Income Taxes Compared: High vs. No Tax States</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 21, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>6 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">Where you live in the US has a massive impact on your take-home pay. Here is a comprehensive comparison of how state income taxes vary, flat tax vs. progressive states, and states with no income tax.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Location, location, location:</strong> Earning $100,000 in California yields a vastly different net salary than earning $100,000 in Texas, purely due to state tax rates. Learn how to run the math before a major move.</div>

      <h2>The state tax landscape</h2>
      <p>US states levy income taxes in three primary formats: progressive brackets (similar to the federal system), flat tax rates (one rate for all income levels), or no income tax at all. Currently, 41 states and Washington D.C. have some form of state income tax, while 9 states charge no state income tax on earned wages.</p>

      <h2>States with no income tax</h2>
      <p>As of 2026, the following nine states do not tax personal earned income:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Alaska</li>
        <li>Florida</li>
        <li>Nevada</li>
        <li>New Hampshire (taxes dividend and interest income, but is phasing this out)</li>
        <li>South Dakota</li>
        <li>Tennessee</li>
        <li>Texas</li>
        <li>Washington (levies a tax on certain high-value capital gains, but no income tax)</li>
        <li>Wyoming</li>
      </ul>
      <p>While no income tax sounds appealing, these states often offset the lost revenue by charging higher sales taxes, property taxes, or corporate levies.</p>

      <h2>States with flat income tax rates</h2>
      <p>Several states charge a single, flat tax rate on all taxable income. Examples include Colorado (4.4%), Illinois (4.95%), Michigan (4.25%), North Carolina (4.5%), and Utah (4.65%). Flat tax systems are simple to calculate but do not adjust tax burden based on earning capacity.</p>

      <h2>High tax progressive states</h2>
      <p>States like California, New York, Hawaii, and New Jersey utilize progressive bracket systems with high top marginal rates. California has the highest state income tax rate in the country, topping out at 13.3% (plus a 1.1% SDI tax) for high earners. New York's top state rate reaches 10.9%. Earning a high salary in these locations requires careful planning to minimize state tax liabilities.</p>

      <h2>Relocation math: An example comparison</h2>
      <p>If you earn $150,000 as a single filer, look at the difference in state income tax alone:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Texas:</strong> $0 state income tax.</li>
        <li><strong>California:</strong> Approximately $11,000 in state income tax.</li>
        <li><strong>New York:</strong> Approximately $9,500 in state income tax.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Before moving for a higher salary, make sure to use our paycheck calculator to evaluate the net cost of state taxes and compare the local cost of living.</p>
